        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "MCP Servers"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An MCP server is an independent process that exposes capabilities \u2014 Tools, Resources, and Prompts \u2014 to any MCP-capable host over a standard JSON-RPC 2.0 protocol. The server owns credentials, calls external APIs, and returns content blocks. The host and the model only see tool names, schemas, and text results."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Anatomy of an MCP server: transport, protocol handler, tools/resources/prompts, credentials"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "The MCP SDK handles transport framing and JSON-RPC dispatch. Your job is to implement three things: list_tools() returning schema definitions, call_tool() executing them, and optionally list_resources() / read_resource() for read-only data."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A Minimal MCP Server"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The smallest useful server exposes one tool. The SDK's decorator pattern maps JSON-RPC method names to Python functions:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# pip install mcp\nfrom mcp.server import Server\nfrom mcp.server.stdio import stdio_server\nfrom mcp import types\nimport asyncio, os, requests\n\napp = Server(\"weather-server\")\n\n@app.list_tools()\nasync def list_tools() -> list[types.Tool]:\n    return [\n        types.Tool(\n            name=\"get_weather\",\n            description=\"Get current weather for a city.\",\n            inputSchema={\n                \"type\": \"object\",\n                \"properties\": {\n                    \"city\": {\n                        \"type\": \"string\",\n                        \"description\": \"City name, e.g. 'Tokyo'\"\n                    }\n                },\n                \"required\": [\"city\"],\n            },\n        )\n    ]\n\n@app.call_tool()\nasync def call_tool(name: str, arguments: dict) -> list[types.TextContent]:\n    if name != \"get_weather\":\n        raise ValueError(f\"Unknown tool: {name}\")\n\n    city = arguments[\"city\"]\n    api_key = os.environ[\"WEATHER_API_KEY\"]   # credential stays here, never leaves\n    resp = requests.get(\n        \"https://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5/weather\",\n        params={\"q\": city, \"appid\": api_key, \"units\": \"metric\"},\n        timeout=8,\n    )\n    resp.raise_for_status()\n    data = resp.json()\n    text = f\"{data['name']}: {data['main']['temp']}\u00b0C, {data['weather'][0]['description']}\"\n    return [types.TextContent(type=\"text\", text=text)]\n\nasync def main():\n    async with stdio_server() as (read, write):\n        await app.run(read, write, app.create_initialization_options())\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    asyncio.run(main())\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Run it: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "python weather_server.py"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". It reads from stdin and writes to stdout \u2014 the transport the MCP client expects for stdio mode. The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "WEATHER_API_KEY"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is read once at startup from the process environment, never visible to callers."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A Multi-Tool Server"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Real servers expose several tools in one "
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Real servers expose several tools. The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "call_tool"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " handler dispatches by name \u2014 keep each case short and delegate to helper functions as the server grows:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from mcp.server import Server\nfrom mcp import types\nimport asyncio, os, requests\n\napp = Server(\"github-server\")\n_TOKEN = os.environ[\"GITHUB_TOKEN\"]\n_BASE = \"https://api.github.com\"\n_HEADERS = {\"Authorization\": f\"Bearer {_TOKEN}\", \"Accept\": \"application/vnd.github+json\"}\n\n@app.list_tools()\nasync def list_tools() -> list[types.Tool]:\n    return [\n        types.Tool(\n            name=\"list_pull_requests\",\n            description=\"List open pull requests for a repository.\",\n            inputSchema={\n                \"type\": \"object\",\n                \"properties\": {\n                    \"owner\": {\"type\": \"string\", \"description\": \"Repo owner\"},\n                    \"repo\":  {\"type\": \"string\", \"description\": \"Repo name\"},\n                    \"state\": {\"type\": \"string\", \"enum\": [\"open\", \"closed\", \"all\"], \"default\": \"open\"},\n                },\n                \"required\": [\"owner\", \"repo\"],\n            },\n        ),\n        types.Tool(\n            name=\"create_issue\",\n            description=\"Create a new issue in a repository.\",\n            inputSchema={\n                \"type\": \"object\",\n                \"properties\": {\n                    \"owner\": {\"type\": \"string\"},\n                    \"repo\":  {\"type\": \"string\"},\n                    \"title\": {\"type\": \"string\", \"description\": \"Issue title\"},\n                    \"body\":  {\"type\": \"string\", \"description\": \"Issue body (Markdown)\"},\n                },\n                \"required\": [\"owner\", \"repo\", \"title\"],\n            },\n        ),\n    ]\n\n@app.call_tool()\nasync def call_tool(name: str, arguments: dict) -> list[types.TextContent]:\n    if name == \"list_pull_requests\":\n        owner = arguments[\"owner\"]\n        repo  = arguments[\"repo\"]\n        state = arguments.get(\"state\", \"open\")\n        resp = requests.get(\n            f\"{_BASE}/repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls\",\n            params={\"state\": state, \"per_page\": 10},\n            headers=_HEADERS, timeout=10,\n        )\n        resp.raise_for_status()\n        prs = resp.json()\n        lines = [f\"PR #{pr['number']}: {pr['title']} (@{pr['user']['login']})\" for pr in prs]\n        return [types.TextContent(type=\"text\", text=\"\\n\".join(lines) or \"No PRs found.\")]\n\n    if name == \"create_issue\":\n        owner = arguments[\"owner\"]\n        repo  = arguments[\"repo\"]\n        resp = requests.post(\n            f\"{_BASE}/repos/{owner}/{repo}/issues\",\n            json={\"title\": arguments[\"title\"], \"body\": arguments.get(\"body\", \"\")},\n            headers=_HEADERS, timeout=10,\n        )\n        resp.raise_for_status()\n        issue = resp.json()\n        return [types.TextContent(type=\"text\", text=f\"Created issue #{issue['number']}: {issue['html_url']}\")]\n\n    raise ValueError(f\"Unknown tool: {name}\")\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "_HEADERS"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " dict is built once at module load time using the token from the environment. Every tool call reuses it without re-reading the env var."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Exposing Resources"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Resources let the server offer readable data \u2014 files, DB rows, API snapshots \u2014 without allowing writes. The host can pass resource content directly into the model's context window via "
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Resources let the server offer readable data without allowing writes. Add "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "list_resources()"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "read_resource()"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " handlers alongside the tool handlers:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from mcp.server import Server\nfrom mcp import types\nimport asyncio, os, pathlib\n\napp = Server(\"filesystem-server\")\nROOT = pathlib.Path(os.environ.get(\"FS_ROOT\", \".\")).resolve()\n\n@app.list_resources()\nasync def list_resources() -> list[types.Resource]:\n    resources = []\n    for path in ROOT.rglob(\"*.md\"):\n        rel = path.relative_to(ROOT)\n        resources.append(types.Resource(\n            uri=f\"file:///{rel}\",\n            name=str(rel),\n            mimeType=\"text/markdown\",\n        ))\n    return resources\n\n@app.read_resource()\nasync def read_resource(uri: str) -> str:\n    # Strip the file:/// prefix and resolve safely within ROOT\n    rel = uri.removeprefix(\"file:///\")\n    target = (ROOT / rel).resolve()\n    # Safety: prevent path traversal outside ROOT\n    if not str(target).startswith(str(ROOT)):\n        raise ValueError(f\"Access denied: {uri}\")\n    return target.read_text(encoding=\"utf-8\")\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The path-traversal guard is critical for any filesystem server. Always resolve paths and confirm they remain within the allowed root before reading."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Error Handling in Tool Handlers"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Two error categories need different handling:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Application errors"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " (bad input, upstream API failure, not found): return a "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "TextContent"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " with an error message. The MCP response sets "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "isError: true"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " and the model receives the text \u2014 it can choose a fallback or inform the user."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Protocol errors"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " (unknown tool name, implementation bug): raise a Python exception. This becomes a JSON-RPC error response and signals to the host that the server cannot handle the request."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from mcp import types\nimport requests\n\n@app.call_tool()\nasync def call_tool(name: str, arguments: dict) -> list[types.TextContent]:\n    if name == \"get_data\":\n        try:\n            resp = requests.get(\"https://api.example.com/data\",\n                                params=arguments, timeout=10)\n            resp.raise_for_status()\n            return [types.TextContent(type=\"text\", text=resp.json()[\"result\"])]\n\n        except requests.Timeout:\n            # Return as a tool error (isError=true) not a protocol exception\n            return [types.TextContent(type=\"text\", text=\"Error: request timed out after 10s\")]\n\n        except requests.HTTPError as exc:\n            status = exc.response.status_code\n            if status == 404:\n                return [types.TextContent(type=\"text\", text=f\"Error: resource not found\")]\n            if status == 429:\n                retry = exc.response.headers.get(\"Retry-After\", \"unknown\")\n                return [types.TextContent(\n                    type=\"text\",\n                    text=f\"Error: rate limited. Retry after {retry}s\"\n                )]\n            return [types.TextContent(type=\"text\", text=f\"Error: upstream returned HTTP {status}\")]\n\n    raise ValueError(f\"Unknown tool: {name}\")\n    # Raising an exception is a protocol-level error (transport failure equivalent).\n    # Only raise for genuinely unknown tool names, not for application errors.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Testing an MCP Server"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Test tool handlers as pure async functions \u2014 no subprocess, no network. Mock at the HTTP boundary:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio, pytest\nfrom unittest.mock import patch, MagicMock\n\n# Import the server module\nimport weather_server   # contains app, list_tools, call_tool\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_list_tools_returns_get_weather():\n    tools = await weather_server.list_tools()\n    names = [t.name for t in tools]\n    assert \"get_weather\" in names\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_call_tool_get_weather():\n    mock_resp = MagicMock()\n    mock_resp.json.return_value = {\n        \"name\": \"Tokyo\",\n        \"main\": {\"temp\": 22.5},\n        \"weather\": [{\"description\": \"clear sky\"}],\n    }\n    mock_resp.raise_for_status = MagicMock()\n\n    with patch(\"weather_server.requests.get\", return_value=mock_resp):\n        result = await weather_server.call_tool(\"get_weather\", {\"city\": \"Tokyo\"})\n\n    assert len(result) == 1\n    assert \"Tokyo\" in result[0].text\n    assert \"22.5\" in result[0].text\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_call_tool_unknown_raises():\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"Unknown tool\"):\n        await weather_server.call_tool(\"nonexistent\", {})\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
